A **Delivery Manager (DM)** is the person responsible for **making sure work is delivered on time, within scope, and with predictable quality**. They focus on *flow*, *process*, and *delivery health* rather than building features themselves.

Below is a **QA-practical explanation**, not a textbook one.

---

## Who is a Delivery Manager (in real life)

Think of the Delivery Manager as the **owner of delivery mechanics**.

They usually handle:

* Sprint / release delivery
* Cross-team coordination
* Risks, dependencies, and blockers
* Delivery metrics (predictability, velocity, cycle time)
* Stakeholder expectations (â€œwill it be done by X?â€)

They **do not**:

* Write requirements (thatâ€™s PO/PM)
* Design solutions (thatâ€™s dev/architect)
* Decide test cases (thatâ€™s QA)
* Approve quality gates alone (thatâ€™s shared)

---

## Where Delivery Manager sits (simplified)

```
Product Manager / PO â†’ WHAT & WHY
Delivery Manager     â†’ WHEN & HOW SMOOTHLY
Tech Lead / Dev      â†’ HOW TECHNICALLY
QA                  â†’ IS IT SAFE & CORRECT
```

The DM is your **main ally** when quality conflicts with deadlines.

